{"key":"processedPost-12795400","value":{"id":12795400,"first":12786134,"last":12867397,"when":1277390665,"utime":"06/24/10 05:44 PM","content":"The purpose of the plenum is to allow a uniform pressure to be exerted over the entire surface of the back of the filter.&nbsp; If that is achieved, the plenum is large enough.&nbsp; If you're putting the blower inside the plenum, other issues with turbulence arise, and testing is going to be required.&nbsp; A suitable anemometer can be had for around $200 and is a good investment if you're engineering your own unit.&nbsp; A good rule of thumb for an external mounted blower is to make the plenum at least as thick as the filter in order to have a space to pressurize, but that's not a hard and fast rule.<br /><br />The bottom line is if the anemometer(or a candle flame for a cheaper alternative) indicates the same amount of airflow over the entire working area, you've achieved laminar flow.<br />RR","title":"Re: Flow hoods.","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}